{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 thresholds for all component-KPIs and then inspected the incident window. The strongest signals overall were socket-related anomalies concentrated on infrastructure and DB components (catalogue-db, orders-db, queue-master, rabbitmq, session-db). However, the allowed root-cause component set for this task is limited to service-level components: carts, catalogue, orders, payment, and user. Among those, prior aggregates showed: carts has CPU and log.row_count spikes (severity ~1.78 and 1.5 respectively); orders shows small CPU and latency upticks (severity ~1.15 and ~1.18); catalogue had minor log.row_count upticks and some memory/socket baseline but not strong service-level faults; payment and user show small row_count/latency upticks. Because traces are unavailable and error logs are empty, we must localize the root cause using metrics and logs restricted to the allowed service set. The next step is to focus only on these five services and produce compact anomaly aggregates (global P95, count in window, anomaly_count, earliest anomaly, max and severity) from the full-series P95 thresholds already required by rules, for both metric.csv and log.csv. This will tell us which allowed service shows the most significant and persistent deviation during the incident window.",
